## STATISTICAL ANALYSIS

Applied:

- Pearson & Spearman Correlation
- Shapiro Normality Testing
- ANOVA
- Kruskal–Wallis Test
- Multiple Linear Regression (with interaction term)

Key Findings:

• Smoking and Genetic Risk significantly predict severity  
• No strong correlation between Treatment Cost and Survival  
• No statistically significant Genetic Risk × Smoking interaction  
• Stage progression did not significantly alter survival in this dataset  

---

## MACHINE LEARNING MODELING

Model: Random Forest Regressor

Target Variables:
- Target_Severity_Score
- Survival_Years

Performance (Severity Model):
- Train R² ≈ 0.96
- Test R² ≈ 0.77

Top Predictors:
1. Smoking
2. Genetic Risk
3. Treatment Cost
4. Alcohol Use
5. Air Pollution

---

## ECONOMIC BURDEN ANALYSIS

• Significant treatment cost variation across countries  
• Higher costs observed in developed healthcare systems  
• Minimal gender-based pricing disparity  
• Treatment cost not significantly associated with longer survival  

